notes:
Dave Ruiter: "Gordon (1974:127) created the Cheumatopsyche rossi group. Not sure why she called it the rossi group as C.pettiti is the senior name. ( Hoffman and Parker 1997 resurrected C.analis as the senior name for C. pettiti and C.analis seems to have been accepted recently.

This group consists of 5 species: C.analis, C.logani, C.robisoni, C.rossi, C.smithi. C. rossi and C.smithi were described, along with the group, by Gordon in 1974 based on minor differences from C.analis and could easily all be the same species. Gordon (1974) used an interesting term (phenocline) for this variability. I always thought cline represented a shift in a character represented by a general shift across a geographical range (eg. many northern limnephilid populations tend to have shorter wings). But I didnt think the extreme range differences represented distinct species. Nimmo (1987) provided a female association for smithi that is quite distinct from C.analis. I have presumed material for all 5 species so I will have to look at the females closer,

C.logani and C. robisoni seem distinct from the other three, but very close to each other and easily confused with C.campyla.

It is likely that many collections, including mine, have been called C.analis or C. camplya and are actually comprised of the others.

I made a little table based on the descriptions of Gordon and Moulton to try and sort it out for me:

(Zhou note: table skipped here.)

Not sure it helps. I went back into my collection and found a lot of material from all over the US that I had called C.analis but with the long basal clasper segment. And lots of NA C. analis material with the 10th apical segment extending above the 10th. Based on Gordons descriptions these would all be C. rossi. However the wide basal portion of the C. analis apical clasper segment seems to occur on all these specimens.

For some reason Moulton thought C.robisoni was most closely related to C. rossi rather than C. logani so he didnt really compare it to C.logani. Moulton thought C.rossi was restricted to high volume springs of the Ozarks.

-Dec 26, 2009

notes:
Light Trap, 9:45-11:00pm

Dave Ruiter:`Gordon seems to have created the Cheumatopsyche helma group as a place to put several confusing taxa she didnt know where else to put C. helma. C. harwoodi harwoodi, C. h. enigma, C. wrighti). One character that does seem consistent among all four is the supposed dark, non-patterned wings. Another character that fits most is the long basal clasper segment. The fact that she created a single species for three male C. harwoodi forms indicates to me there was still a great deal of confusion and uncertainty.

Your two C. harwoodi specimens (08NBEPT-0972 & 0838) do not look like any of the C.harwoodi forms to me because of the clasper. I have called them C. near wrighti because of the apical clasper segment having a wide base and the spotted wing color. The basal segment of 0838 is broad and long, and the apical segment is very broad at the base and curved very differently. The fairly wide lateral surface of the 9th and short 10th lobes also seems to place them closer to C.wrighti than C.harwoodi. I have a series from NY that I called C.wrighti. Yours is very close to the NY specimens but your clasper is slightly different.

-Dec 26, 2009.

notes:
Dave Ruiter: "Gordon (1974:127) created the Cheumatopsyche rossi group. Not sure why she called it the rossi group as C.pettiti is the senior name. ( Hoffman and Parker 1997 resurrected C.analis as the senior name for C. pettiti and C.analis seems to have been accepted recently.

This group consists of 5 species: C.analis, C.logani, C.robisoni, C.rossi, C.smithi. C. rossi and C.smithi were described, along with the group, by Gordon in 1974 based on minor differences from C.analis and could easily all be the same species. Gordon (1974) used an interesting term (phenocline) for this variability. I always thought cline represented a shift in a character represented by a general shift across a geographical range (eg. many northern limnephilid populations tend to have shorter wings). But I didnt think the extreme range differences represented distinct species. Nimmo (1987) provided a female association for smithi that is quite distinct from C.analis. I have presumed material for all 5 species so I will have to look at the females closer,

C.logani and C. robisoni seem distinct from the other three, but very close to each other and easily confused with C.campyla.

It is likely that many collections, including mine, have been called C.analis or C. camplya and are actually comprised of the others.

I made a little table based on the descriptions of Gordon and Moulton to try and sort it out for me:

(Zhou note: table skipped here.)

Not sure it helps. I went back into my collection and found a lot of material from all over the US that I had called C.analis but with the long basal clasper segment. And lots of NA C. analis material with the 10th apical segment extending above the 10th. Based on Gordons descriptions these would all be C. rossi. However the wide basal portion of the C. analis apical clasper segment seems to occur on all these specimens.

For some reason Moulton thought C.robisoni was most closely related to C. rossi rather than C. logani so he didnt really compare it to C.logani. Moulton thought C.rossi was restricted to high volume springs of the Ozarks.

-Dec 26, 2009

notes:
genitalia cleared.

Dave Ruiter: "Gordon (1974:127) created the Cheumatopsyche rossi group. Not sure why she called it the rossi group as C.pettiti is the senior name. ( Hoffman and Parker 1997 resurrected C.analis as the senior name for C. pettiti and C.analis seems to have been accepted recently.

This group consists of 5 species: C.analis, C.logani, C.robisoni, C.rossi, C.smithi. C. rossi and C.smithi were described, along with the group, by Gordon in 1974 based on minor differences from C.analis and could easily all be the same species. Gordon (1974) used an interesting term (phenocline) for this variability. I always thought cline represented a shift in a character represented by a general shift across a geographical range (eg. many northern limnephilid populations tend to have shorter wings). But I didnt think the extreme range differences represented distinct species. Nimmo (1987) provided a female association for smithi that is quite distinct from C.analis. I have presumed material for all 5 species so I will have to look at the females closer,

C.logani and C. robisoni seem distinct from the other three, but very close to each other and easily confused with C.campyla.

It is likely that many collections, including mine, have been called C.analis or C. camplya and are actually comprised of the others.

I made a little table based on the descriptions of Gordon and Moulton to try and sort it out for me:

(Zhou note: table skipped here.)

Not sure it helps. I went back into my collection and found a lot of material from all over the US that I had called C.analis but with the long basal clasper segment. And lots of NA C. analis material with the 10th apical segment extending above the 10th. Based on Gordons descriptions these would all be C. rossi. However the wide basal portion of the C. analis apical clasper segment seems to occur on all these specimens.

For some reason Moulton thought C.robisoni was most closely related to C. rossi rather than C. logani so he didnt really compare it to C.logani. Moulton thought C.rossi was restricted to high volume springs of the Ozarks.

-Dec 26, 2009

notes:
Light Trap, 9:45-11:00pm

Dave Ruiter:`Gordon seems to have created the Cheumatopsyche helma group as a place to put several confusing taxa she didnt know where else to put C. helma. C. harwoodi harwoodi, C. h. enigma, C. wrighti). One character that does seem consistent among all four is the supposed dark, non-patterned wings. Another character that fits most is the long basal clasper segment. The fact that she created a single species for three male C. harwoodi forms indicates to me there was still a great deal of confusion and uncertainty.

Your two C. harwoodi specimens (08NBEPT-0972 & 0838) do not look like any of the C.harwoodi forms to me because of the clasper. I have called them C. near wrighti because of the apical clasper segment having a wide base and the spotted wing color. The basal segment of 0838 is broad and long, and the apical segment is very broad at the base and curved very differently. The fairly wide lateral surface of the 9th and short 10th lobes also seems to place them closer to C.wrighti than C.harwoodi. I have a series from NY that I called C.wrighti. Yours is very close to the NY specimens but your clasper is slightly different.

-Dec 26, 2009

notes:
Dave Ruiter: "Gordon (1974:127) created the Cheumatopsyche rossi group. Not sure why she called it the rossi group as C.pettiti is the senior name. ( Hoffman and Parker 1997 resurrected C.analis as the senior name for C. pettiti and C.analis seems to have been accepted recently.

This group consists of 5 species: C.analis, C.logani, C.robisoni, C.rossi, C.smithi. C. rossi and C.smithi were described, along with the group, by Gordon in 1974 based on minor differences from C.analis and could easily all be the same species. Gordon (1974) used an interesting term (phenocline) for this variability. I always thought cline represented a shift in a character represented by a general shift across a geographical range (eg. many northern limnephilid populations tend to have shorter wings). But I didnt think the extreme range differences represented distinct species. Nimmo (1987) provided a female association for smithi that is quite distinct from C.analis. I have presumed material for all 5 species so I will have to look at the females closer,

C.logani and C. robisoni seem distinct from the other three, but very close to each other and easily confused with C.campyla.

It is likely that many collections, including mine, have been called C.analis or C. camplya and are actually comprised of the others.

I made a little table based on the descriptions of Gordon and Moulton to try and sort it out for me:

(Zhou note: table skipped here.)

Not sure it helps. I went back into my collection and found a lot of material from all over the US that I had called C.analis but with the long basal clasper segment. And lots of NA C. analis material with the 10th apical segment extending above the 10th. Based on Gordons descriptions these would all be C. rossi. However the wide basal portion of the C. analis apical clasper segment seems to occur on all these specimens.

For some reason Moulton thought C.robisoni was most closely related to C. rossi rather than C. logani so he didnt really compare it to C.logani. Moulton thought C.rossi was restricted to high volume springs of the Ozarks.

-Dec 26, 2009

notes:
light trap, weather conditions: partly sunny.

Dave Ruiter: "Gordon seems to have created the Cheumatopsyche helma group as a place to put several confusing taxa she didnt know where else to put C. helma. C. harwoodi harwoodi, C. h. enigma, C. wrighti). One character that does seem consistent among all four is the supposed dark, non-patterned wings. Another character that fits most is the long basal clasper segment. The fact that she created a single species for three male C. harwoodi forms indicates to me there was still a great deal of confusion and uncertainty.

......

Your C.enigma specimen (08NBEPT-0466) could very well be C.enigma and I have labeled as C. harwoodi near enigma - at least the wing is very dark without obvious pale markings. But the clasper seems too long and broad and the lateral angle of the 9th too wide and acute. The 10th also seems quite wide and the 10th lobe has a fairly obvious latero-ventral lobe. I have a series I had called C.enigma but the 10th does not look at all like your 0466 - they dont have the ventro-lateral lobe on the 10th."

-Dec 26, 2009.

notes:
light trap.

"07ONCAD-0137 - Roger called this one C.campyla. I would tend to agree although the apical segment of the inferior appendage is a little short. The only other option I see is C.logani, which, so far, is a NW US species. I have some OR material I called C.logani back in 2004 but unfortunately it was all cleared with KOH so that won't be of much use for DNA. And, as I now look at it some more, I am not sure of the logani determination. Your 0137 specimen looks more like the Gordon's logani figure than my OR logani specimen. So I have called your 0137 specimen C.campyla. There are other collections I have called C.logani in WA (Rich Zack) and MT (Bob Newell). I don't know if I cleared them all or not. And I am not sure what they were preserved in but I can ask for them. They are from the 2000's."-Dave Ruiter, Dec 3, 2009.

Note: Dave put a determination label "C. nr. ela" on the voucher, which according to his text note should be a mistake.- XIn Zhou, Sep 3, 2010.

notes:
Seq identical to C. analis. u.v. light: #690306, ROM Field Pty.

Dave Ruiter: "Gordon (1974:127) created the Cheumatopsyche rossi group. Not sure why she called it the rossi group as C.pettiti is the senior name. ( Hoffman and Parker 1997 resurrected C.analis as the senior name for C. pettiti and C.analis seems to have been accepted recently.

This group consists of 5 species: C.analis, C.logani, C.robisoni, C.rossi, C.smithi. C. rossi and C.smithi were described, along with the group, by Gordon in 1974 based on minor differences from C.analis and could easily all be the same species. Gordon (1974) used an interesting term (phenocline) for this variability. I always thought cline represented a shift in a character represented by a general shift across a geographical range (eg. many northern limnephilid populations tend to have shorter wings). But I didnt think the extreme range differences represented distinct species. Nimmo (1987) provided a female association for smithi that is quite distinct from C.analis. I have presumed material for all 5 species so I will have to look at the females closer,

C.logani and C. robisoni seem distinct from the other three, but very close to each other and easily confused with C.campyla.

It is likely that many collections, including mine, have been called C.analis or C. camplya and are actually comprised of the others.

I made a little table based on the descriptions of Gordon and Moulton to try and sort it out for me:

(Zhou note: table skipped here.)

Not sure it helps. I went back into my collection and found a lot of material from all over the US that I had called C.analis but with the long basal clasper segment. And lots of NA C. analis material with the 10th apical segment extending above the 10th. Based on Gordons descriptions these would all be C. rossi. However the wide basal portion of the C. analis apical clasper segment seems to occur on all these specimens.

For some reason Moulton thought C.robisoni was most closely related to C. rossi rather than C. logani so he didnt really compare it to C.logani. Moulton thought C.rossi was restricted to high volume springs of the Ozarks.

-Dec 26, 2009
